Suitable in size and armament to be a stand in for an Inquisition Cruiser in the classic tabletop wargame Battlefleet Gothic. This is mostly a re-mix of Italianmoose sculpts; the hull based on the Italianmoose Imperial cruiser, both Italianmoose Chaos cruiser bridge versions are mixed together, the Italianmoose battle barge underbridge is included in the superstructure and that's also where the wings and gun sections come from, the prow is from the Italianmoose strike cruiser. The engines are built from scratch sculpt by me.

I am not affiliated with GW in any way. Please don't reupload this on Shapeways and the like for commercial use (though you're welcome to upload them to get them printed that way for yourself).

These are my versions of the Nova and Gladius Frigates from that no longer available tabletop game of epic space battles in the Gothic Sector. I have patterned these after those found on the electronic game of the same name. I have tried to get the scale correct and I hope they are close. I really enjoyed making them and they look awesome printed!

All of them were test printed on an FDM printer at .08 layer height with a .4 nozzle. Angle them up at 45 degrees and be careful while removing supports.

I have placed a starter 3mm hole in the bottoms. I use a 1/8 drill bit and 1/8 styrene rod.. but use what you would like.

These were made from scratch using base primitives.

A Thunderhawk Ordinance proxy for Battlefleet Gothic.

A game buddy asked for some prints and I couldn't find a suitable model.

As per 2nd pic...
- The scale is based on the Imperial Attack Craft Models by Mkhand_Industries
https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2626812
- The shape is heavily borrowed from a similar model on $h@p#w@y$.

While i very much like Mkhand's models (and have printed a number for my Imperial fleet) i've found that the wings are very delicate on my filament printer... as such the thunderhawk wings are all a little chunkier (minimum 0.5mm).

Has now been netfabb'd.

Have test printed. works but it's like tiny tiny (as per last pic).
Re pic: the small ones are what the file produces. the big one is 250% scale just to test that stuff was there and printing.
Re other pic: (not finished) paint just to add some colour.
The teeny-tiny ones do look ok once they're on stands. And there's a fair amount of tricky support cleanup. enjoy.

Note: For my marine fleet i've printed these at 133%. just to get a bit more 'detail' and less blobbular. these are the yellowish ones. note that for sticking them to the bases i just use some chopped filament, was easier than printing the bases with stands as they were coming out horrible.
